50|$|The 21st {{century has}} {{witnessed}} {{an increase in}} scholarly interest in the integrated use of archaeology as an additional research component in arriving at {{a better understanding of}} the historical Jesus by illuminating the socio-economic and political background of his age. <b>James</b> <b>Charlesworth</b> states that few modern scholars now want to overlook the archaeological discoveries that clarify the nature of life in Galilee and Judea during the time of Jesus.|$|E
50|$|<b>James</b> <b>Charlesworth</b> {{states that}} few modern {{scholars}} {{now want to}} overlook the archaeological discoveries that clarify the nature of life in Galilee and Judea {{during the time of}} Jesus. Jonathan Reed states that chief contribution of archaeology {{to the study of the}} historical Jesus is the reconstruction of his social world. An example archaeological item that Reed mentions is the 1961 discovery of the Pilate Stone, which mentions the Roman prefect Pontius Pilate, by whose order Jesus was crucified.|$|E
