5000|$|Gabbatha (Lithostrōtos): This {{location}} is referenced {{only once in}} the New Testament in John 19:13. This is an Aramaic term that refers {{to the location of}} the trial of Jesus by Pontius Pilate and the Greek name of Lithostrōtos (λιθόστρωτος) meaning stone pavement also refers to it. It was likely a raised stone platform where Jesus faced Pilate. <b>James</b> <b>Charlesworth</b> considers this location of high archaeological significance and states that modern scholars believe this location was in the public square just outside the Praetorium in Jerusalem and was paved with large stones.|$|E
